    {
      "id": "9adffdf1_a99088ed",
      "file_path": "vid-app-common/src/main/java/org/onap/vid/services/AAIServiceTree.java",
      "patchset_number": 10,
      "line": 21,
      "message": "Yes. ONAP uses Google Style Guide with slight omdifications ( https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Java+code+style ) and rule 3.3.1 forbids wildcard imports ( https://google.github.io/styleguide/javaguide.html#s3.3.1-wildcard-imports ).\n\nThis is because wildcart import can cause problems - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/147454/why-is-using-a-wild-card-with-a-java-import-statement-bad",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2795,
        "name": "Lukasz Biniek",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "lukasz.biniek@nokia.com",
        "username": "Biniek"
      },
      "updated": "2019-01-10 08:56:31.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "9adffdf1_f3551f50",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "9adffdf1_891fc46b",
      "file_path": "vid-app-common/src/test/java/org/onap/vid/aai/util/CacheProviderWithLoadingCacheTest.java",
      "patchset_number": 10,
      "line": 48,
      "message": "I see no advantage in using random names over static ones here. There are however some disadvantages - for example when test (randomly) fails we have no idea why, and we have no way to reproduce it without having those random values. Also when random test fails it encourages developer to just the test again instead of fixing it.\n\nSome of tests here actually can randomly fail - for example in test cacheProvider_sameProviderSupportDifferentKV if two randomly generated names are the same then test fails. Using static names could easly avoid such situation.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2795,
        "name": "Lukasz Biniek",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "lukasz.biniek@nokia.com",
        "username": "Biniek"
      },
      "updated": "2019-01-10 08:56:31.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "9adffdf1_33cf272b",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
